Population and sample

Population:
the largest collection of entities for which we have an interest at a particular time
Parameter:
measures of the population, denoted by Greek letters (e.g., \(\mu\) and \(\sigma ^2\) for the population mean and variance)
Sample:
a subset of the population
Statistic:
measures of the sample, denoted by Roman letters (e.g., \(\bar x\) and \(s^2\) for the sample mean and variance)

Population and sample

Sample space:
the set of all possible outcomes
Event:
a set of outcomes of interest
Probability of an event:
the relative frequency of this set of outcomes over an infinitely large number of trials
Randomly sampling:
a sampling technique in which each sample has an equal probability of being chosen.

Suppose you cook a pot of soup for you family. You add some salt into it. How do you know if the soup is salty enough for your family?

Probability of an event

The probability of an event E denoted by P(E), always satisfies \(0 \le P(E) \le 1\).

If outcomes A and B are two events that cannot both happen (i.e., A and B are mutually exclusive or disjoint), then \(P(A \text{ or } B) = P(A) + P(B)\).

  • The symbol {} is used as shorthand for the phrase âthe eventâ.
  • \(\{A \cup B\}\) is the event that either \(A\) or \(B\) occurs, or they both occur.
  • \(\{A \cap B\}\) is the event that both \(A\) and \(B\) occur simultaneously.
  • \(\bar{A},\) called the complement of \(A,\) is the event that \(A\) does not occur. Note, \(P(\bar{A})=1-A\)

Laws and Rules

Multiplication Law

Definitions:

  • \(A\) and \(B\) are independent events if \(P(A \cap B)=P(A) \times P(B)\)

  • \(A\) and \(B\) are dependent events if \(P(A \cap B) \neq P(A) \times P(B)\)

Multiplication Law If \(A_{1}, A_{2}, \ldots, A_{k}\) are mutually independent events, then

\[ P\left(A_{1} \cap A_{2} \cap \cdots \cap A_{k}\right)=P\left(A_{1}\right) \times P\left(A_{2}\right) \times \cdots \times P\left(A_{k}\right) \]

Demo: The ENV203 students survey. What is the possibility that a randomly selected subject is male from North China?

env203$Hometown <- c("South", "North")[env203$Hometown]
table(env203$Gender, env203$Hometown)
##         
##          North South
##   Female    18    20
##   Male       3     9

           data = env203,
           margins = c(TRUE, TRUE))
##  --------------------------------- 
##          --------Hometown--------- 
##  Gender     North   South   Total  
##  --------------------------------- 
##  Female        18      20      38  
##  Male           3       9      12  
##                                    
##  Total         21      29      50  
##  ---------------------------------
p_a_and_b <- 3 / 50
p_a_and_b
## [1] 0.06

\(A\) is the event that a randomly selected subject is male.

\(B\) is the event that a randomly selected subject is from North China.

p_a <- table(env203$Gender)[2] / nrow(env203)
p_b <- table(env203$Hometown)[1] / nrow(env203)
p_a * p_b
##   Male 
## 0.1008

\(P(A \cap B) \neq P(A) \times P(B)\). Thus \(A\) and \(B\) are dependent events.

Addition Law

For any two events \(A\) and \(B\),

\[ P(A \cup B)=P(A)+P(B)-P(A \cap B) \]

For two mutually exclusive events \(A\) and \(B\),

\[ P(A \cup B)=P(A)+P(B) \times \bar{A} \]

Demo: The ENV203 students survey.

\(A\) is the event that a randomly selected subject is male.

\(B\) is the event that a randomly selected subject is from North China.

The possibility that a randomly selected subject is male or is from North China is \(P(A \cup B)=P(A)+P(B)-P(A \cap B)\).

p_a_or_b <- p_a + p_b - p_a_and_b
p_a_or_b
## Male 
##  0.6

Conditional probability

  • The conditional probability of \(B\) given \(A\) is written as \(P(B \mid A)\).

\[ P(B \mid A)=\frac{P(B \cap A)}{P(A)} ; P(A) \neq 0 \]

  • If \(A\) and \(B\) are independent events, then

\[ P(B \mid A)=P(B)=P(B \mid \bar{A}) \]

  • If \(A\) and \(B\) are dependent events, then

\[ P(B \mid A) \neq P(B) \neq P(B \mid \bar{A}) \]

Demo: The ENV203 students survey.

\(A\) is the event that a randomly selected subject is male.

\(B\) is the event that a randomly selected subject is from North China.

The possibility that a randomly selected subject is from North China given the subject is male is \(P(B \mid A)=\frac{P(B \cap A)}{P(A)}\).

p_b_given_a <- p_a_and_b / p_a
p_b_given_a
## Male 
## 0.25

Total Probability Rule

For any two events \(A\) and \(B\),

\[ P(B)=P(B \mid A) \times P(A)+P(B \mid \bar{A}) \times P(\bar{A}) \]

Derivation:

\(B\) occurs with or without \(A,\) so \(P(B)=P(B \cap A)+P(B \cap \bar{A})\). From the definition of conditional probability, \(P(B \cap A)=\) \(P(B \mid A) \times P(A)\) and \(P(B \cap \bar{A})=P(B \mid \bar{A}) \times P(\bar{A}) .\) Simple substitution gives the results.

A set of events \(A_{1}, \ldots, A_{k}\) is exhaustive if at least one of the events must occur.

Let \(A_{1}, \ldots, A_{k}\) be mutually exclusive and exhaustive events. The unconditional probability of \(B, P(B),\) can be written as the weighted average of the conditional probabilities of \(B\) given \(A\).

\[ P(B)=\sum_{i} P\left(B \mid A_{i}\right) \times P\left(A_{i}\right) \]

Bayesâ Rule

\[ P(B \mid A)=\frac{P(A \mid B) \times P(B)}{P(A \mid B) \times P(B)+P(A \mid \bar{B}) \times P(\bar{B})} \]

Derivation: From the definition of conditional probability,

\[ \begin{array}{l} P(B \mid A)=P(B \cap A) / P(A) \\ P(B \cap A)=P(A \mid B) \times P(B) \end{array} \]

From the total probability rule,

\[ P(A)=P(A \mid B) \times P(B)+P(A \mid \bar{B}) \times P(\bar{B}) \]

Substitute (3) and (2) into (1).

Greek and Roman letters

  • Greek civilization was the origin of Roman civilization.

Data types

Two data types

Normally, we treat data as two types:

  • Qualitative data, or categorical data, place data in descriptive groups. e.g.Â home prefecture, Judo rank, weatherâ¦
    • Nominal variables have neither rank nor distance.
    • Ordinal variables have rank but no distance.
  • Quantitative data, or numerical data, take numerical values. They have both rank and distance. e.g.Â temperature, weightâ¦
    • Discrete variables often take on integers.
    • Continuous variables can take on any value.
Data types.
Type Sub-type Rank Distance Examples
qualitative (categorical) nominal no no sex, weather
ordinal yes no preferences, grades
quantitative (numerical) discrete yes yes age, book quantity
continuous yes yes weight, height

Distinguish qualitative data and quantitative data with scale, which has two components:

  • Rank is the ability to tell that one value is greater than another
  • Distance is the ability to make sense of the âmagnitudeâ of the distance between two values

Knowing the types of your data would help you choose the appropriate distribution to analyze you data, tables and graphs to present your data.

Titanic

RMS Titanic was a British passenger liner operated by the White Star Line that sank in the North Atlantic Ocean in the early morning hours of 15 April 1912, after striking an iceberg during her maiden voyage from Southampton to New York City. Of the estimated 2,224 passengers and crew aboard, more than 1,500 died, making the sinking one of modern historyâs deadliest peacetime commercial marine disasters.

The following table shows the fate of passengers on the fatal maiden voyage of the ocean liner âTitanicâ, summarized according to economic status (class), sex, age and survival.

Find the following probabilities:

  1. A randomly selected subject is a surviving girl from the 2nd class.
  2. A randomly selected subject is a dead male crew.
  3. A randomly selected subject is a woman or is from the 3rd class.
  4. A randomly selected subject is a man given that he/she survived.
  5. A randomly selected subject is a boy given that he/she is from the 1st class.
